  "prompt": "How likely will LASIK vision deteriorate with age if one had stable prescription before the operation?",
  "response": "The likelihood of vision deterioration after LASIK depends on several factors:\n\n1. Initial Stability\n- Most surgeons recommend LASIK only after prescription has been stable for at least 1-2 years\n- Stable prescription reduces risk of future vision changes\n\n2. Age-Related Changes\n- Natural aging processes like presbyopia are inevitable\n- Around age 40-45, near vision typically begins to decline\n- This isn't directly related to LASIK but normal eye aging\n\n3. Typical Long-Term Outcomes\n- Approximately 95-98% of patients maintain improved vision after LASIK\n- About 2-5% might need enhancement/touch-up procedures\n- Minor regression can occur in first few years post-surgery\n\n4. Factors Influencing Potential Deterioration\n- Original prescription strength\n- Age at time of surgery\n- Overall eye health\n- Healing response\n- Corneal thickness\n- Underlying health conditions\n\n5. Recommended Monitoring\n- Annual eye exams\n- Follow-up with LASIK surgeon\n- Track any vision changes\n\nWhile some vision changes are possible, most patients maintain significantly improved vision years after LASIK, especially if prescription was stable pre-surgery.\n\nIndividual results can vary, so consulting an ophthalmologist for personalized assessment is recommended.",
